      "role": "user",
      "content": "i see. so it's basically a choice between a fixed document or a living one. but if you look at how originalism is actually applied in court cases today, it seems like it's often used to strike down rights that people take for granted now. doesn't that make it less of a neutral legal theory and more of a tool for a specific political outcome?",
